In article <archie.763880057@qin.CS.Berkeley.EDU>, archie@qin.CS.Berkeley.EDU (Archie Cobbs) writes:
|> I apologize if this is a FAQ or recent topic... I checked the FAQ
|> and recent subject headings but saw no reference, but could also
|> have gotten the spelling wrong...
|> 
|> Question is: what is "El Gamal"? (a public key scheme?)
|> 
|> Thanks,
|> -Archie
|> 

El Gamal is a public key and signature scheme based on the difficulty of computing discrete logarithms in fields (as opposed to the difficulty of factoring which is the underlying assumption for RSA.)  An El Gamal signature box is not able to do El Gamal encryption -- the two algorithms are different.  Check out the reference Taher El Gamal "A Public Key Cryptosystem and a Signature Scheme Based on Discrete Logarithms" in IEEE Transactions on Information Theory, Vol IT-31, No 4, July 1985.

-- Rolf



